Introduction ¶

Finding blockbuster hit movies is a crucial part of any movie exective's job. Hollywood runs on big movies and finding the combination of acting, plot, and characters that piques the interest of movie-goers is vital. Continual poor box-office performance can lead to exectives of producing studios to get axed. Therefore, we want to conduct a study on what traits top-selling movies tend to have. In categorizing top-blockbuster hits, we hope that these features can be used in a predictive model to show what traits movie exectives might want to have in their movies in the future, to spark big box-office turnouts.

We plan for our study to outline the entire data science lifecycle. We will begin this analysis by gathering data on movies. To do this, we will download data from the IMDB database that contains every movie ever logged onto the database with information genre, description, title, actors, characters, crew members, and average ranking. This will give us sufficient data to analyze the traits of movies that recieve high engagement with viewers. The one primary weakness of this dataset is that we do not have box office data merged to it. However, we aim to use a smaller dataset from the kaggle TMDB movie revenue box office prediction challenge. After examining the featurs of movies in the larger dataset, we can make a more informed model for the smaller dataset in order to make predictions. We will dive into more specific analyses or actors, directors, and produces to see if there are more granular trends that might give rise to that receive a lot of user engagement.

Later, to tease out specific relationships among actors, directors, and movies to analyze the "social network" phenomenon in the hollywood movie industry, we will be prototyping and visualizing multiple different graph networks through python's networkx package to see how specific relationships among actors and directors correspond to user engagement on IMDB and how they relate to movie revenues.

Datasets¶

The large IMDB datasets that we pulled data from are linked in the title of this section. The specific documentation is listed on the page, but here we will give a short summary of the main characteristics of each of the datasets to help explain their relevance to our analysis.

  • name.basics.tsv.gz => This table lists actors, directors, and crew members by their name constants or codes that show up in other tables and then maps to their actual names. This will act as a lookup table to get specific names of agents in the hollywood industry.
  • title.crew.tsv.gz => This dataset lists the codified title of the movie along with the crew members (writers and directors) that participated in the given movie
  • title.principals.tsv.gz => This table gives information on the primary actors, directors, and crew members of every movie in the dataset along with relative ordering among the people's individual roles
  • title.basics.tsv.gz => This gives relevant information about every movie including release year, runtime, title, age distinction, and the year of release for every movie in the dataset
  • title.ratings.tsv.gz => This table gives the average rating and number of reviews for every movie in the dataset

\ Since this dataset includes millions of different movie titles, the easiest way to work the data at this volume is to export it to a SQL database, and access the data as needed through queries. Because we want to be able to demonstrate this process within our tutorial, we will read in the data once, do a bit of cleaning and export it to a db using python's sqlite3. This package allows programmers to create, read, and write to serverless databases all within the programming language of their choice.

Writing the Data to SQL¶

This next cell is responsible for writing all of the tables after preprocessing and filtering into the SQL database. On the python side, we did limited data cleaning and filtering because those operations are very costly to do on the python side and will often hit upon many errors. Because SQL tables have predefined schemas, it will be faster to simply data processing like filtering and joins on that side and then doing more complicated operations on the smaller dataset in python. More a more in-depth comparison between Python and SQL for data processing tasks, check out this interesting article. From now on, we will be reading in smaller selections of data from the database every time we want to conduct an analysis.

In [ ]:
#This segment of code only needs to be run once!

#These lines of code, push all of the tables to SQL with names so that when they are queried, we know which table to pull from
name_table.to_sql(name='principals', con=conn, if_exists='replace', index=False)
actor_data.to_sql(name='names', con=conn, if_exists='replace', index=False)
basic_data.to_sql(name = 'media', con = conn, if_exists='replace', index = False)
ratings.to_sql(name = 'ratings', con = conn, if_exists='replace', index = False)
crew_data.to_sql(name = 'crew', con = conn, if_exists='replace', index = False)

#After pushing the data to SQL, commit all the changes to the DB
conn.commit()

Distribution of Movies with High IMDB Engagement¶

The first plot that we are going to make is one that teases out how frequently movies become popular. Making this plot will be an important starting point to jump from for any further analysis because we want to have some idea of the underlying distribution of movie popularity. Because we do not have access to a larger dataset of box office metrics, we will be using IMDB ratings as a rough proxy for popularity on the larger dataset.

Power Law Distribution Interpretation¶

As we can see from the plot above, using the number of ratings that a movie receives on IMDB follow a power law distribution. For more on the significance and just how commonly this distribution appears, look at this fascinating article that describes more on the phenomenon. However, the main idea is that in some sense people are often watching and reviewing movies based on what their friends watch, or what movies have been most heavily promoted on social media. This means that is likely some universal connection between IMDB users that's causing only a few movies to garner so much attention. In this case, the power law distribution implies that many (if not most) of the total reviews come from a small subset of the most popular movies in the IMDB. This makes sense in context with the fact that many different types of popular media also tend to follow this distribution.

Now, it might be prudent to see if there are underlying factors causing this. For instance, IMDB reviewers could be drawn in by specific actors, directors, or genres that all tend to garner more attention than most others. The next step is to make different versions of this graph, but instead of focusing on movies, we want to focus more specifically on crew members.

Next let's investigate the theoretical assumption that we have been hinting at throughout this analysis: using number of IMDB votes as a proxy for revenue. Now that we have a sample of data with both box office revenue and the number of votes, we can investigate how valid this assumption is.

From this plot, we can see a decently strong positive association between the two. In other words, a higher number of IMDB votes seems to roughly correspond to higher revenue. But from this scatter plot, it appears that the error of any regression line between the two would be reasonably high. In addition, there appear to be clear outliers in this dataset, so using this as a proxy (especially with non-penalized regression, may be improperly fit). Let's investigate the correlation between the two to just see the strength of the relationship.

Again the correlation is reasonably high at 0.63, but the errors and outliers as indicated by the scatter plot make us skeptical that the benefits from having more training data for the model. In addition, the richness of the kaggle dataset will likely outweigh any deficencies in the volume of movies that we can use to train and test our model on.

Examining Potential Factors for Predictive Box Office Modelling¶

At this stage, we are ready to start using the traits from a wealth of movies to predict the box office revenue of movies. The first step in this process is selecting the factors. For right now, we are going to do some exploration on a few key factors that may potentially help develop a predictive model.

  • Genre: Certain types of movies may generally garner more attention from viewers. For instance, it seems reasonably likely that action movies will perform better than musicals in the box office. Thus, while I don't think it will be the most important factor, I think there could be some relationship between genre and number of ratings. Note that we cannot use this factor as-is, since regressions will not work with categorical factors. Therefore, we need to employ a procedure called one-hot encoding. This process turns a categorical column into a boolean column with 0 to represent false and 1 to represent true. We will do a little but of exploration to select the genres that might be most impactful to use.

  • Region: The globe does not have an even distribution of movie successes. Often one a few regions tend to dominate in movie sales. It's also possible that since different genres are more popular in different regions, we could add an interaction term in our regression between region and genre. Some more EDA will also flesh out this relationship. We can derive this variable from the original language of release and the primary spoken language.

  • Weighted Director Rating: This is a factor that we will attempt to derive from variables that we have in the IMDB dataset. The intuition behind this factor is that if directors receive high average ratings then they are more likely to produce top-hit movies in the future. Further, if they have been in a large number of movies, then that establishes even more confidence that they will produce high-selling movies. More details about this factor will be determined below when we actually construct the factor.

  • Budget: It seems to make perfect sense that if a movie has a higher budget behind it, it is likely to make more revenue. High budget movies seem likely to be the ones that have the most advertising behind them (because movie studios want to make their money back on their high investments). As we touched on in the introduction, movie producers make large investments in specific cast members, directors, and writers in the hopes that they will make money on the movie. This factor will likely be highly indicative of a big box-office hit.

Weighted Rating Calculation Attempt¶

NOTE: Can someone explain why exactly we made the factor like this bc I don't remember why lol

As shown in the plot above, there are multiple problems that we want to overcome in developing a useful factor. We want a metric that finds the true arithmetic mean of a director's rating which is the rating of a movie that they directed times the number of votes that the movie received. ...

metric is calulated as:

sum(averagerating{i} * numVotes{i}) / total(numVotes)

and then normalized by z-score

In [ ]:
#calculate the raw score (total rating)
directors_exploded['score'] = directors_exploded['averageRating'] * directors_exploded['numVotes']
In [ ]:
#calculate the weighted scores, normalized as a z-score

#apply z_score standardization
weighted_score_df = directors_exploded.groupby('directors')['score'].sum() / directors_exploded.groupby('directors')['numVotes'].sum()
weighted_score_df = weighted_score_df.reset_index()
weighted_score_df = weighted_score_df.rename({0:'weighted_score'}, axis = 1)
weighted_score_df['weighted_score'] = (weighted_score_df['weighted_score'] - weighted_score_df['weighted_score'].mean()) / weighted_score_df['weighted_score'].std()

Based on this histogram, the data appear to have a slighly skewed distribution, but they seem to be approximately normally distributed. Note that the standardization routine (although traditionally done on normally distributed variables) does not change the shape of the underlying distribution as it is only a linear transformation on the data points. We can test this initial hypothesis with a quantile-quantile plot that matches quantiles of this distribution up with quantiles of the normal distribution. For more on the statistical interpretation of that kind of plot read this piece. However, the big idea is that the closer the quantiles match up (meaning that there is a one-to-one relationship between the quantiles of the weighted score distribution and the normal distirubtion), then the more confident we can be that the distribution of weightted scores is normal.

One Hot Encoding¶

For the categorical variables that we plan on using in the models, they will need to be one hot encoded. One hot encoding transforms a categorical variable into a numeric variable, by transforming all unique row values into columns and then each row values corresponds to 0, meaning that the original row did not have the specific variable and 1 meaning that the original row did have that variable. For a longer-form, intuitive explanation, check out this article. We will need to do this for our two categorical variables. Note that this may introduce some problems with having too many sparse features, but we think that penalized regression will help solve this issue.

In [ ]:

# function to pick out director value from list of dicts in "crew" col
def director_from_crew(x):

    crew = eval(x)
    
    for member in crew:
        if member['job'] == 'Director':
            return member['name']
        
    return ''

Penalized Regression (Ridge & LASSO)¶

Given the large number of factors that we have present in this dataset, it may be fruitful to pursue a penalized regression. Penalized regression helps in the case that we have a lot of factors, and we aren't as confident that each one is actually helping our predictive model out of sample. The idea behind penalized regression is that there is a "cost" to pay for decreasing variance in the in-sample prediction. This cost is controlled by a parameter called lamdba, or alpha in the scikit-learn library, which indicates how much of a decrease in variance is needed to justify the increase in bias. In using this kind of regression, we hope that there is some implicit feature selection in that low beta regressors will become either closer to 0 or exactly 0.

For this we will compare two different methods of penalized regression: Lasso Regression and Ridge Regression and we will interpret results at the end of the experiment. In addition, we will use a technique called cross validation which will be explained below to tune the alpha hyperparameter for what we hope will produce the best out of sample performance.

train_index_cutoff = int(0.8 * len(filtered_movie_data.index))

regression_cols = np.concatenate((language_cols.columns.values, genre_cols.columns.values,['numVotes', 'runtime', 'budget', 'weighted_score']))
x_data_train = filtered_movie_data[regression_cols].iloc[:train_index_cutoff]

Conclusion ¶

Our regression models tend perform pretty poorly overall when it comes to predicting movie revenue. Using penalized regressions such as Ridge and Lasso tend to improve models in the sense that the error becomes slightly reduced and yet all of our mean squared errors across all the models had a magnitude of 10^16. Considering our scale for revenue, the variable we were looking to predict, was in U.S dollars, an error of this large a magnitude is quite significant. It would be interesting to explore how well other types of regression models would perform but given the order of magnitude for our error calculations, it may be appropriate to reconsider our input variable entirely. Perhaps factors such as budget, genre, languages spoken, or average ratings from previous works are not as impactful on a movie's projected revenue as much as the combination of the people involved with the movie itself.

Future analysis of blockbuster films would explore more of the graph data that we produced through more social network analysis techniques. Our current analysis highlighted some of the well-established directors and actors in the industry based on the number of movies that they were involved in. After all, actors tend to become popular if they star in well-received movies, the ones that tend to rake in the most revenue. Different networks and combinations of actors and directors may very well perform differently from one another and could be an important factor in predicting the revenue that a movie would produce.
